{
  "text": "Here M g,n denotes the moduli space of closed Riemann surfaces of genus g and n punctures, \u03c6 the Liouville field, X a collective label for the matter fields, and {O k } a generic assortment of local operators. To compute amplitudes in the presence of h boundaries, in the language of critical string theory we would of course integrate over the moduli space of M g,n,h of Riemann surfaces with h holes, specifying appropriate boundary conditions for all the fields. In the language of quantum gravity, FZZT boundary conditions have the simple interpretation of introducing a 'weight' for each boundary length \u2113 i [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ,",
  "correct_citation": {
